value.value: An arithmetic operation by which the product of two numbers is computed, symbolized by x or *.
Elevated skin lesions associated with the presence of purulent material.
Epidermolysis bullosa characterized by separation of the skin through the lamina lucida resulting in blister formation. It includes lethal and non-lethal variants.

Chronic lung disease requiring treatment with oxygen for at least 28 days and with a spectrum of severity from mild to severe, that predominantly affects premature infants. While the radiologic pattern is typical in the closer to term patient, the pattern in the small preterm infant is very non-discrete and variable.
Fats composed of three fatty acid chains linked to a glycerol molecule.
The reemergence of lymphoblastic lymphoma in childhood after a period of remission.
The convex bulge in the gum below a tooth caused by the underlying structure of the tooth root.
The screw that secures an abutment onto a dental implant.
The isthmus joining North America and South America, extending from the southern border of Mexico to the northern border of Colombia.
Pharmacologic agents administered to a neonate at birth.
The muscle of the upper arm that extends the forearm.
Leading to or causing leukemia.
Tumstatin (245 aa, ~27 kDa) is encoded by the human COL4A3 gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of angiogenesis.
This gene plays a role in transport of ceramides and diacylglycerol lipids.

Human CERT1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 5q13.3 and is approximately 156 kb in length. This allele, which encodes ceramide transfer protein, is involved in the regulation of trafficking of ceramides and diacylglycerol lipids. Mutation of the gene is associated with autosomal dominant mental retardation type 34.
An anatomic structure formed by the crossing of the two optic nerves under the hypothalamus.

A carcinoma that arises from the penis. Risk factors include phimosis and human papillomavirus infection. The majority of penile carcinomas are squamous cell carcinomas. The most frequent clinical presentation is an irregular mass in the glans of the penis. Treatment includes surgical management and radiation therapy.
A potent, selective and orally bioavailable, difluoropyrrolidine-based inhibitor of dipeptidyl peptidase 4 (DPP-4), with hypoglycemic activity.
The phosphate ester of metronidazole, a synthetic nitroimidazole derivative with antiprotozoal and antibacterial activities.
A Burkitt lymphoma occurring in adults.

The sodium salt form of lometrexol, a folate analogue antimetabolite with antineoplastic activity. As the stereoisomer of 5,10-dideazatetrahydrofolate, lometrexol selectively inhibits glycinamide ribonucleotide formyltransferase (GARFT), the enzyme that catalyzes the first step in the de novo purine biosynthetic pathway, thereby inhibiting DNA synthesis and leading to an inhibition of tumor cell proliferation.  The agent has been shown to be active against tumors that are resistant to the folate antagonist methotrexate, but causes severe, dose-limiting toxicities.

A malignant germ cell tumor that arises from the testis. It predominantly affects young men. Seminoma is the most frequently seen malignant testicular germ cell tumor, followed by embryonal carcinoma and yolk sac tumor.

An orally bioavailable agonist of the human beta-3 adrenergic receptor (ADRB3), with muscle relaxing, neuroprotective and potential antineoplastic activities.  Upon oral administration, mirabegron binds to and activates ADRB3, which leads to smooth muscle relaxation. Mirabegron also restores sympathetic stimulation in mesenchymal stem cell (MSC) niches, inhibits JAK2-mutated hematopoietic stem cell (HSC) expansion and blocks the progression of myeloproliferative neoplasms (MPNs). Lack of sympathetic stimulation of the MSC and HSC niche is associated with the development of MPNs.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic with broad-spectrum antibacterial activity isolated from Streptomyces bluensis and many other Streptomyces species.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic derived from kanamycin A, exhibiting a similar cochlear toxicity profile to that of kanamycin A.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic isolated from Micromonospora sagamiensis var. nonreducans. Micronomicin is an analog of gentamicin and has broad-spectrum activity against both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic isolated from Streptomyces ribosidificus.
A localized hepatocellular carcinoma that occurs during adulthood and it is amenable to surgical resection.
